<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-solving-logarithmic-equations-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Solving Logarithmic Equations I</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.4 Logarithms II
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Solve logarithmic equations in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To familiarise Learners with the equivalence between logarithmic and exponential forms of equations, and to use this equivalence to solve logarithmic equations.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="act-log-exponential-match">
        <title>Find the Pair: Logarithms and Exponentials</title>

        <introduction>
            <p>
                A logarithmic equation and its equivalent exponential form say exactly the
                same thing in two different languages. The key is to raise the base to both
                sides:
                <me>
                    \log_b(A) = n \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad A = b^n
                </me>
                In this activity you will practise recognising these equivalent forms, and
                then use the exponential form to solve for <m>x</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <task xml:id="task-match-pairs">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Each logarithmic equation in Column A has exactly one matching
                    exponential form in Column B. Draw a line connecting each pair.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-log-exp-matching">
                    <caption>
                        Column A: logarithmic equations. Column B: exponential forms
                        (in a different order). Draw lines to connect each matching pair.
                    </caption>
                    <image xml:id="img-log-exp-matching" width="100%">
                        <description>
                            Two columns of eight items each. Column A contains eight
                            logarithmic equations labelled A to H. Column B contains
                            eight exponential forms labelled 1 to 8 in a shuffled order.
                            Students draw lines connecting each matching pair.
                        </description>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[font=\small]
                            %
                            % LEFT COLUMN: Logarithmic equations (A-H)
                            % Row centres at y = 0, -1.5, -3.0, -4.5, -6.0, -7.5, -9.0, -10.5
                            % Boxes extend +/-0.55 from centre
                            %
                            % Row A  (y = 0)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-0.55) rectangle (5.8,0.55);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,0) {A.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,0) {$\log_2(x+2)=4$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            % Row B  (y = -1.5)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-2.05) rectangle (5.8,-0.95);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,-1.5) {B.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,-1.5) {$\log_3(x-1)=2$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,-1.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            % Row C  (y = -3.0)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-3.55) rectangle (5.8,-2.45);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,-3.0) {C.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,-3.0) {$\log_5(x)=3$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,-3.0) circle (2.5pt);
                            % Row D  (y = -4.5)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-5.05) rectangle (5.8,-3.95);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,-4.5) {D.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,-4.5) {$\log_4(2x)=3$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,-4.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            % Row E  (y = -6.0)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-6.55) rectangle (5.8,-5.45);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,-6.0) {E.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,-6.0) {$\log_2(x)=-2$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,-6.0) circle (2.5pt);
                            % Row F  (y = -7.5)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-8.05) rectangle (5.8,-6.95);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,-7.5) {F.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,-7.5) {$\log_3(x+5)=0$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,-7.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            % Row G  (y = -9.0)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-9.55) rectangle (5.8,-8.45);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,-9.0) {G.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,-9.0) {$\log_{10}(x-3)=2$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,-9.0) circle (2.5pt);
                            % Row H  (y = -10.5)
                            \draw[thick] (0,-11.05) rectangle (5.8,-9.95);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (0.15,-10.5) {H.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (0.75,-10.5) {$\log_2(3x+1)=5$};
                            \filldraw (5.8,-10.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            %
                            % RIGHT COLUMN: Exponential forms (shuffled)
                            % Boxes from x=7.7 to x=13.5
                            %
                            % Row 1  (y = 0)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-0.55) rectangle (13.5,0.55);
                            \filldraw (7.7,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,0) {1.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,0) {$x = 5^3$};
                            % Row 2  (y = -1.5)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-2.05) rectangle (13.5,-0.95);
                            \filldraw (7.7,-1.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,-1.5) {2.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,-1.5) {$x+5 = 3^0$};
                            % Row 3  (y = -3.0)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-3.55) rectangle (13.5,-2.45);
                            \filldraw (7.7,-3.0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,-3.0) {3.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,-3.0) {$x-1 = 3^2$};
                            % Row 4  (y = -4.5)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-5.05) rectangle (13.5,-3.95);
                            \filldraw (7.7,-4.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,-4.5) {4.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,-4.5) {$3x+1 = 2^5$};
                            % Row 5  (y = -6.0)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-6.55) rectangle (13.5,-5.45);
                            \filldraw (7.7,-6.0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,-6.0) {5.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,-6.0) {$x-3 = 10^2$};
                            % Row 6  (y = -7.5)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-8.05) rectangle (13.5,-6.95);
                            \filldraw (7.7,-7.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,-7.5) {6.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,-7.5) {$x+2 = 2^4$};
                            % Row 7  (y = -9.0)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-9.55) rectangle (13.5,-8.45);
                            \filldraw (7.7,-9.0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,-9.0) {7.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,-9.0) {$2x = 4^3$};
                            % Row 8  (y = -10.5)
                            \draw[thick] (7.7,-11.05) rectangle (13.5,-9.95);
                            \filldraw (7.7,-10.5) circle (2.5pt);
                            \node[anchor=west,font=\small\bfseries] at (7.85,-10.5) {8.};
                            \node[anchor=west] at (8.45,-10.5) {$x = 2^{-2}$};
                            %
                            % Column headings
                            %
                            \node[font=\normalsize\bfseries] at (2.9,1.1) {Column A};
                            \node[font=\normalsize\bfseries] at (10.6,1.1) {Column B};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    The correct pairs are:
                </p>
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Column A</cell>
                        <cell>Matches</cell>
                        <cell>Column B</cell>
                        <cell>Exponential form</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>A</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>6</cell>
                        <cell><m>x+2=2^4</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>B</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>3</cell>
                        <cell><m>x-1=3^2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>C</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>1</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=5^3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>D</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>7</cell>
                        <cell><m>2x=4^3</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>E</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>8</cell>
                        <cell><m>x=2^{-2}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>F</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>2</cell>
                        <cell><m>x+5=3^0</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>G</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>5</cell>
                        <cell><m>x-3=10^2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>H</cell><cell><m>\leftrightarrow</m></cell><cell>4</cell>
                        <cell><m>3x+1=2^5</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
                <note>
                    <p>
                        The most common mismatches to watch for: students may pair
                        <m>\log_2(x)=-2</m> with <m>x+2=2^4</m> by incorrectly reading the
                        <m>-2</m> and the <m>2</m> as related, and may pair
                        <m>\log_3(x+5)=0</m> with <m>x-1=3^2</m> by ignoring the base
                        entirely. Both errors reveal a shaky grasp of the conversion rule
                        and are worth addressing in class discussion.
                    </p>
                </note>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-solve-for-x">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Using your matched pairs, complete the table below. Evaluate each power
                    and solve for <m>x</m>. Leave answers as fractions where necessary.
                </p>
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <col width="10%" halign="center"/>
                    <col width="30%"/>
                    <col width="30%"/>
                    <col width="30%"/>
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Pair</cell>
                        <cell>Logarithmic equation</cell>
                        <cell>Exponential form</cell>
                        <cell>Solution (<m>x=</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>A <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_2(x+2)=4</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>B <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_3(x-1)=2</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>C <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_5(x)=3</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>D <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_4(2x)=3</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>E <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_2(x)=-2</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>F <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_3(x+5)=0</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>G <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_{10}(x-3)=2</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>H <m>\leftrightarrow</m> __</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_2(3x+1)=5</m></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <tabular halign="center" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor">
                    <col width="10%" halign="center"/>
                    <col width="28%"/>
                    <col width="28%"/>
                    <col width="34%"/>
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Pair</cell>
                        <cell>Logarithmic equation</cell>
                        <cell>Exponential form</cell>
                        <cell>Solution (<m>x=</m>)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>A <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 6</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_2(x+2)=4</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x+2=2^4=16</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=14</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>B <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 3</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_3(x-1)=2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x-1=3^2=9</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=10</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>C <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 1</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_5(x)=3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=5^3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=125</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>D <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 7</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_4(2x)=3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2x=4^3=64</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=32</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>E <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 8</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_2(x)=-2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=2^{-2}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=\dfrac{1}{4}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>F <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 2</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_3(x+5)=0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x+5=3^0=1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=-4</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>G <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 5</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_{10}(x-3)=2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x-3=10^2=100</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=103</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>H <m>\leftrightarrow</m> 4</cell>
                        <cell><m>\log_2(3x+1)=5</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3x+1=2^5=32</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>x=\dfrac{31}{3}</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-reflect-unusual">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Look back at your solutions table and answer the following questions.
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            One equation produced a <em>negative</em> solution for <m>x</m>.
                            Which one? Check that it is still a valid solution by substituting
                            back into the original logarithmic equation.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            One equation produced a <em>fractional</em> solution for <m>x</m>.
                            Which one? What does a negative exponent mean, and how does it
                            produce a fraction?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Equation F has a right-hand side of 0. Before solving, what value
                            must <m>x+5</m> equal? Why does <em>any</em> base raised to the
                            power 0 give that value?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                <p>
                    <alert>Question 1.</alert> Equation F: <m>\log_3(x+5)=0</m> gives
                    <m>x=-4</m>. Check: <m>\log_3(-4+5)=\log_3(1)=0</m> &#x2713;.
                    The solution is valid because the argument <m>x+5=1</m> is positive,
                    even though <m>x</m> itself is negative.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Question 2.</alert> Equation E: <m>\log_2(x)=-2</m> gives
                    <m>x=2^{-2}=\frac{1}{4}</m>. A negative exponent means a reciprocal:
                    <m>b^{-n}=\frac{1}{b^n}</m>, so <m>2^{-2}=\frac{1}{4}</m>.
                    This is a useful reminder that logarithms can be negative (when the
                    argument is between 0 and 1) and that the solution need not be an integer.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Question 3.</alert> When the right-hand side is 0, the exponential
                    form gives <m>x+5=b^0=1</m>. Any non-zero base raised to the power 0
                    equals 1 because <m>b^1 \div b^1 = b^{1-1} = b^0</m> must equal 1.
                </p>
                <note>
                    <p>
                        Questions 1 and 3 address a frequent misconception: students often
                        reject a negative value of <m>x</m> by confusing the domain restriction
                        (the <em>argument</em> must be positive) with a restriction on
                        <m>x</m> itself. This reflection task is designed to surface and
                        correct that confusion before it causes problems in harder equations.
                    </p>
                </note>
            </solution>
        </task>

    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    2 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Instruct Learners on how to solve logarithmic equations by rewriting them in exponential form and evaluating the resulting power.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <insight>
        <p>
            When solving logarithmic equations, the key step is to rewrite the equation in exponential form. This allows us to evaluate the power and solve for <m>x</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            The general conversion rule is: <m>\log_b(x) = n \iff x = b^n</m>. This means that if we have a logarithmic equation, we can raise the base to both sides to get an equivalent exponential equation. Once in exponential form, we can evaluate the power and solve for <m>x</m> using basic algebraic techniques.
        </p>
    </insight> 


    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Solve for <m>x</m>: <m>\log_2(x) = 3</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Rewrite in exponential form using <m>\log_b(a) = c \iff b^c = a</m>:
            </p>
            <md>
                <mrow>2^3 \amp= x</mrow>
                <mrow>x \amp= 8</mrow>
            </md>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Solve for <m>x</m>: <m>\log_3(x + 1) = 2</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Rewrite in exponential form:
            </p>
            <md>
                <mrow>3^2 \amp= x + 1</mrow>
                <mrow>9 \amp= x + 1</mrow>
                <intertext>Subtract 1 from both sides:</intertext>
                <mrow>x \amp= 8</mrow>
            </md>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Solve for <m>x</m>: <m>\log_4(x - 2) = 1</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Rewrite in exponential form:
            </p>
            <md>
                <mrow>4^1 \amp= x - 2</mrow>
                <mrow>4 \amp= x - 2</mrow>
                <intertext>Add 2 to both sides:</intertext>
                <mrow>x \amp= 6</mrow>
            </md>
        </solution>
    </example> 

